<paragraph blockId="27.[113,1089,609,889]" pageId="27" pageNumber="684">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,172,609,633]" pageId="27" pageNumber="684">Note.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName=": BELLAMY (2008:" authorityYear="1508" box="[176,337,610,633]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Agrilaxia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="684" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tristis">
<emphasis box="[176,337,610,633]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="684">Agrilaxia tristis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described from 
<specimenCount box="[544,668,609,633]" pageId="27" pageNumber="684" type="female">two females</specimenCount>
and it resembles very much 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": BELLAMY (2008:" authorityYear="1500" box="[954,1088,610,633]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Agrilaxia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="684" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bongrandi">
<emphasis box="[954,1088,610,633]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="684">A. bongrandi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(compare 
<figureCitation box="[218,346,641,665]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="4.[825,862,1206,1225]" captionTargetBox="[151,1128,220,1546]" captionTargetId="figure-10@4.[151,1126,219,1542]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 1–8. Agrilaxia, dorsal aspect. 1 – Agrilaxia cacao sp. nov., holo- type ♀, 7.2 mm; 2 – A. bongrandi Cobos, 1972, J (Route de Cacao), 6.0 mm; 3 – A.claudei Cobos, 1972, ♀ (Bélizon), 8.0 mm; 4 – A. tristis Cobos, 1972, ♀ (Saul), 7.2 mm; 5 – A. elegans sp. nov., holotype J, 7.8 mm; 6 – A. cordicollis sp. nov., holotype J, 6.5 mm; 7 – A. glabra sp. nov., holotype ♀, 6.0 mm; 8 – A. sulcifrons sp. nov., holotype J, 6.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740764" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740764/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="684">Figs 2 and 4</figureCitation>
) differing from it by the more angulate pronotum, fused black, pronotal stripes (forming one, large central spot), slightly different colouration (compare 
<figureCitation box="[951,1081,673,697]" captionStart="Figs 1–8" captionStartId="4.[825,862,1206,1225]" captionTargetBox="[151,1128,220,1546]" captionTargetId="figure-10@4.[151,1126,219,1542]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 1–8. Agrilaxia, dorsal aspect. 1 – Agrilaxia cacao sp. nov., holo- type ♀, 7.2 mm; 2 – A. bongrandi Cobos, 1972, J (Route de Cacao), 6.0 mm; 3 – A.claudei Cobos, 1972, ♀ (Bélizon), 8.0 mm; 4 – A. tristis Cobos, 1972, ♀ (Saul), 7.2 mm; 5 – A. elegans sp. nov., holotype J, 7.8 mm; 6 – A. cordicollis sp. nov., holotype J, 6.5 mm; 7 – A. glabra sp. nov., holotype ♀, 6.0 mm; 8 – A. sulcifrons sp. nov., holotype J, 6.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740764" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740764/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="684">Figs 2 and 4</figureCitation>
) and by the longer and more acute spines on posterior margins of the anal tergite and ventrite (compare 
<figureCitation box="[217,370,737,761]" captionStart="Figs 17–29. 17–19" captionStartId="8.[443,480,1278,1297]" captionTargetBox="[158,1127,224,1565]" captionTargetId="figure-9@8.[151,1110,219,1514]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs 17–29. 17–19 – anal tergites (17 – Agrilaxia glabra sp. nov., 18 – A. tristis sp. nov., 19 – A. caudata sp. nov.). 20–22 – anal ventrites (20 – A. glabra sp. nov., 21 – A. tristis sp. nov., 22 – A. caudata sp. nov.). 23 – most important diagnostic characters of Agrilaxia spp. (schematically): a – lateroposterior pronotal depressi- ons; b – basal pronotal tubercles; c – transverse basal depression; d – prognathous/ non-prognathous mouth parts; e – lateral margin of pronotum;f – “agriloid” carina; g – humeral swelling; h – elytral epipleura; i – posthumeral carina; j – anal ventrite; k – anal tergite. 24–29 – form of anterior prosternal margin, schematically (24 – flat or slightly convex, 25 – slightly grooved, 26 – deeply grooved, 27 – with longitudinal, lamelliform carina, 28 – with transverse rolled up carina, 29 – with medial perpendicular, peg-like spine). Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740768" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740768/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="684">Figs 18 and 21</figureCitation>
). The male differs from female only by the slender body and the green sutural stripe (golden in female). Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[585,662,769,793]" captionStart="Figs 30–39" captionStartId="9.[113,150,1516,1535]" captionTargetBox="[148,1042,221,1489]" captionTargetId="figure-11@9.[135,1064,212,1496]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figs 30–39.Aedeagi. 30 – Agrilaxia tristis Cobos, 1972; 31 – A. elegans sp. nov.; 32 – A. cordicollis sp. nov.; 33 – A. sulcifrons sp. nov.; 34 – A. convexifrons sp. nov.; 35 – A. caudata sp. nov.; 36 – A. prolonga sp. nov.; 37 – A. guianensis sp. nov.; 38 – A. sp. A; 39 – A. sp. B. Not to same scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740770" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740770/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="684">Fig. 30</figureCitation>
) is prolonged, narrowly spindle-shaped, parameres sharply pointed and somewhat curved apically, median lobe sharply pointed.
</paragraph>
